    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "so if they're basically acting like a brake to stop me from hurting myself, does that mean they're just sitting there in the muscle until i rest? how do they actually get cleared out of the system? like do they just disappear or does something else come in to clean it up?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "They don't just sit there forever; your body immediately ramps up blood flow to the area, acting like a delivery truck to pick up the waste products. Specialized cells called the Cori cycle take over, scavenging the lactate and converting it into glucose in your liver for later use. Meanwhile, the hydrogen ions wash away or are buffered by your muscles' natural chemicals, effectively neutralizing the burn. So, your body actually recycles these byproducts rather than just letting them disappear.",
